=====Usage notes=====
As the past participle of '''prove''', {{m|en|proven}} is sometimes still discouraged, and {{m|en|proved}} is preferred (â€œhave provedâ€ rather than â€œhave provenâ€). However, they are both about equally common in US English, and both are used and considered correct in UK English. In UK English, â€œprovedâ€ is more common,<ref name=oed>{{R:Lexico|prove}}</ref><ref name="ahd">{{R:American Heritage 2000|prove}}</ref><ref name="mw">{{R:Merriam Webster Online|prove}}</ref> but not, for example, in the very common expression â€œinnocent until proven guiltyâ€ (rarely â€œinnocent until proved guiltyâ€).

In addition, as an attributive adjective, ''proven'' is much<ref name="mw"/><ref name=oed/> more commonly used,<ref name="ahd"/> and {{m|en|proved}} is widely proscribed â€“ â€œa proven methodâ€, not â€œa proved methodâ€.

Historically, ''proved'' is the older form, while ''proven'' arose as a Scottish variant â€“ see [[proven#Etymology|etymology]]. Used in legal writing from the mid-17th century, it entered literary usage more slowly, only becoming significant in the 19th century, with the poet {{w|Alfred, Lord Tennyson}} among the earliest frequent users (presumably for reasons of meter).<ref name="mw"/> In the 19th century, ''proven'' was widely discouraged, and remained significantly less common through the mid-20th century (''proved'' being used approximately four times as often); by the late 20th century it came to be used about equally often in US English.<ref name="mw"/>

